Adjusting in light of Buttigieg dropping out.
Due to SC strength but hard to call
I'm in too many of these Dem primary questions and my errors are correlated. So time to hedge. Hedge Biden.
Updating with new prior after 538 has incorporated this weekend's results.
Adjusting, given Biden's recent South Carolina victory.

In spite of a small lead for Sen. Sanders in recent polls, I believe the demographic and political similarities between Virginia and it’s Carolina neighbors to the south will play out in former VP Biden’s favor. Giving him a slight edge here. https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/va/virginia_democratic_primary-6920.html
For this forecast, I used the crowd forecast, the prediction market [1] and the FiveThirtyEight’s forecast for Super Tuesday primaries [2]. I scaled the forecast to the top 3 candidates only.
This is very close. https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-primary-forecast/virginia/ Slight weight to Sanders on momentum in other states, despite Biden momentum in polls.
Updating to reflect favorable polling data for Biden.
Klobuchar and Bloomberg seem to be slipping nation-wide. Additionally Biden is polling well in NC and I believe that to be correlated to Southern and Western NC
updating post Nevada
Using 538 as a prior and adjusting towards Bernie due to Nevada results.
Purely on 538s aggregation of polls.

This is the State to watch!!! It does not matter if my forecast is wrong. Whoever wins this state will have the best chance at beating Donald Trump in the general election, period. This is such a tough state because Virginian’s are playing close attention to the issues and the candidates than any other state. So (I may get in trouble for saying this) most Virginian’s are voting with their mind and not with their emotions.
The Monmouth University Poll on the VIRGINIA DEM PRIMARY POLL just came out.
https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/18/bloomberr-sanders-biden-top-virginia-primary-115743
I used the crowd forecasts and the prediction market [1] for this forecast, but scaled them to the top 3 candidates.
Biden has dropped a lot here. Sanders close. Still give Klobuchar a dark horse chance. It is not that I don’t like Mayor Pete but his support in early rounds does not seem to be sustained.
Starting here based on knee-jerk gut check. Will update with subsequent research and developments.

In my opinion, Bloomberg has a shot here because of all the government employees resident in Virginia. I don't think they like Sanders very much, Buttigieg is the kind of policy wonk (or policy wonk wannabe) that they're comfortable with, but they're not put off by Bloomberg's ambition to have the state regulate every aspect of human life, no matter how trivial.
Again, moderates will prevail.
Being a relatively moderate state, the Sanders/Warren wing should be soundly beaten by the more centrist candidates.
They didn’t like Bernie before, Pete seems the moderate even though he isnt
